me.wobblyyyy.pathfinder2

Class Pathfinder

  • java.lang.Object
    • me.wobblyyyy.pathfinder2.Pathfinder

  • public class Pathfinder
extends java.lang.Object
    The highest-level interface used for interacting with Pathfinder. This class is designed to give you complete (or near complete) control over your robot's movement, whether autonomous or manually controlled. There are a couple of key concepts you'll need to understand in order to effectively make use of this class - namely, Trajectory, Translation, PointXY/PointXYZ, and Angle. Additionally, the tick() method is essential to operate Pathfinder. I'd encourage you to go look at some documentation for the project to get a decent idea of what's going on, but hey, that's up to you. Good luck... I guess? Maybe? Yeah.

    There's some useful functionality in these methods:

    • defaultTickUntil(double, Supplier, BiConsumer)
    • defaultAndThen(Consumer, double, Supplier, BiConsumer)
    ... and there's a bunch of overloads for those methods, too. I wish Java had optional parameters, so I wouldn't have to make quite a few overload methods, but alas... oh well. Anyways, those methods are as follows.
    • defaultTickUntil()
    • defaultTickUntil(double)
    • defaultTickUntil(Supplier)
    • defaultTickUntil(BiConsumer)
    • defaultTickUntil(double, Supplier)
    • defaultTickUntil(double, BiConsumer)
    • defaultTickUntil(Supplier, BiConsumer)
    • defaultTickUntil(double, Supplier, BiConsumer)
    • defaultAndThen()
    • defaultAndThen(Consumer)
    • defaultAndThen(double)
    • defaultAndThen(Supplier)
    • defaultAndThen(BiConsumer)
    • defaultAndThen(Consumer, double)
    • defaultAndThen(Consumer, double, Supplier, BiConsumer)
    • defaultAndThen(Consumer, Supplier)
    ... there's a good chance I'm missing some, but you can go find those if you'd like. Each of those methods has a different set of parameters. If you don't supply one of those parameters, the default value will be used. You can modify the default values as follows:
    • setDefaultOnCompletion(Consumer)
    • setDefaultTimeout(double)
    • setDefaultShouldRun(Supplier)
    • setDefaultOnTick(BiConsumer)

      • Pathfinder

        public Pathfinder(Robot robot,
                  FollowerGenerator generator,
                  java.lang.String... doNotLoad)
        Create a new Pathfinder instance.
        Parameters:
        robot - the Pathfinder instance's robot. This robot should have an odometry system that can report the position of the robot and a drive system that can respond to drive commands. This object may not be null or, an exception will be thrown.
        generator - a generator used in creating followers. This generator functions by accepting a Trajectory and a Robot and returning a follower. If you're unsure of what this means, or what you should do here, you should probably use the "generic follower generator," as it's the simplest. This object may not be null, or an exception will be thrown.
        doNotLoad - a set of Strings that specify to Pathfinder which plugins it should NOT load. If any of the plugins that attempt to automatically load are inside of the doNotLoad list, they won't be loaded. This is here in case you depend on a file which modifies the list of plugins that are automatically loaded whenever an instance of Pathfinder is created. If you decide you don't want that plugin to be loaded, add it's name to this list, and you should be all good.

      • getRecorder

        public MovementRecorder getRecorder()
        Get Pathfinder's movement recorder.
        • Start recording by getting Pathfinder's recorder and using the MovementRecorder.start() method. This will reset the current recording (so if you recorded something and then want to start over, this is how you would do that) and set the isRecording boolean to true. While this is true, whenever you call tick(), the recorder will record information on Pathfinder's current movement.
        • Once you've finished recording, use the MovementRecorder.stop() method to stop recording information. You can access this recorded data by using the MovementRecorder.getRecording() method.
        • Now, to play back movement, it's pretty simple. You just use the MovementPlayback.startPlayback(MovementRecording) method to start the playback, and then use tick() to continue playing the movement back.
        • Because everything is done on a single thread, it's quite easy to stop or start recording, and you won't have any issues with doing just that.
        Returns:
        Pathfinder's movement recorder.

      • getPlayback

        public MovementPlayback getPlayback()
        Get Pathfinder's movement playback manager.
        • Start recording by getting Pathfinder's recorder and using the MovementRecorder.start() method. This will reset the current recording (so if you recorded something and then want to start over, this is how you would do that) and set the isRecording boolean to true. While this is true, whenever you call tick(), the recorder will record information on Pathfinder's current movement.
        • Once you've finished recording, use the MovementRecorder.stop() method to stop recording information. You can access this recorded data by using the MovementRecorder.getRecording() method.
        • Now, to play back movement, it's pretty simple. You just use the MovementPlayback.startPlayback(MovementRecording) method to start the playback, and then use tick() to continue playing the movement back.
        • Because everything is done on a single thread, it's quite easy to stop or start recording, and you won't have any issues with doing just that.
        Returns:
        Pathfinder's movement playback manager.

      • tick

        public Pathfinder tick()
        "Tick" Pathfinder once. This will tell Pathfinder's execution manager to check to see what Pathfinder should be doing right now, and based on that, move your robot. This method is required to operate Pathfinder and should be run as frequently as possible. Not executing this method will cause the library to not function at all.

        As of Pathfinder2 0.6.1, this method will tick two other things BEFORE the executor manager. Those are as follows:

        1. Scheduler (getScheduler())
        2. Zone processor (getZoneProcessor())
        Also as of Pathfinder2 0.6.1, this method will tick two other things AFTER the executor manager. Those are...
        1. Playback manager (getPlayback())
        2. Recording manager (getRecorder())

        Returns:
        this instance of Pathfinder, used for method chaining.

      • setTranslation

        public Pathfinder setTranslation(Translation translation)
        Set a translation to the robot. This is how to manually move your robot. If, for example, you're in TeleOp, and you'd like to drive your robot according to some joystick inputs, this is the method you should use.

        Calling this method will immediately update the robot's translation. However, if the robot is still under the control of a trajectory or follower or executor, the translation you set will have next to no effect. As soon as the follower/trajectory/executor is ticked again with the tick() method, the translation will be set to whatever the Follower says the translation should be.

        Parameters:
        translation - the translation to set to the robot. This translation should be RELATIVE, meaning forwards is forwards for the robot, not forwards relative to you.
        Returns:
        this instance of Pathfinder, used for method chaining.
